A timeless place, as old-fashioned as possible. Visits and observations take place in the evening in small groups (5), by volunteers full of goodwill and kindness, ready to share their interest in astronomy. Under the dome (which we opened and turned ourselves :)), I was able to admire, on a beautiful clear night, Venus and the moon. I was like a child, happy and excited!

Exceptional visit to this observatory from another time, in the heart of the Latin Quarter. Guided tour by a volunteer from the astronomical association. You will learn more about the manufacture of the optics of the glasses and you will be able to operate the telescope. Possibility of seeing the moon and the rings of Saturn on a clear day. Superb panorama of Paris and possibility of zooming in on the monuments to admire their details
With the √éle de la Cit√© in the background, go straight on Rue Saint-Jacques and the Sorbonne University will be on your right. Sorbonne High School is on the left.

Atypical place. Breathtaking and privileged view from the roofs of Paris. Visit to the optical, roughing and polishing workshops. Possibility of using the telescope located under the dome. Reservation essential (group of 6 people)

I had the chance to visit the Sorbonne observatory with a guide (reservation by telephone). I was able to observe the moon and Jupiter and we had a 360¬∞ view of Paris. Incredible experience thanks to the passionate and exciting guide!

It was built in the 17th century under the leadership of Colbert. This Parisian Observatory is the point through which the Paris Meridian (that of Greewich) passes. It is also a small museum of old measuring instruments. To discover.
Unusual place in the heart of Paris. Come and admire a beautiful view of Paris among amateurs making their telescope!
Very beautiful
When you visit the Sorbonne observatory, you have the impression of taking a leap into the past and into space. Memorable experience.
Extremely friendly and welcoming staff, it made me very happy
